After examining the input, it becomes clear that the depth increases incrementally as we move from the root 'f' through a single chain of descendants: f->g->h->i->j->k->l->m. Each line in the input represents an edge between two nodes.

The height of the root node is therefore the number of edges in this longest path. Let's count them:

f->g (1)
g->h (2)
h->i (3)
i->j (4)
j->k (5)
k->l (6)
l->m (7)

Since 'm' is a leaf node (it has no children), the height of the root node 'f' is 7.
